nano <file name> will create file.

interpiter mention to the top of file for bash use the following:
#!/bin/bash

use command "ls -l" to see permission of file which give the rwx for read write and execute where we can see the 3 section 1st for
user 2nd for network group and 3rd is for everyone

to change permission for file use the following command :
chmod u+x <file name>

chmod = change mode 
u for user 
+ to add permission 
x if for execute permission
 
